{"key":"processedPost-9515313","value":{"id":9515313,"first":9514659,"last":9515313,"when":1230615630,"utime":"12/30/08 07:40 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />I'm secretly trying to steer people away from 1/2 pint jars.. it's out dated <br /></blockquote><br /><br />Every day we get a thread started by someone who used full pint jars rather than half pints and they've stalled out.<br /><br />There's lots of reasons not to use the full pints, but for those who insist, they should at least make the mix up on the dry side.&nbsp; Take away at least ten percent of the water.&nbsp; You can put it in later with the dunk.&nbsp; Another problem with full pints is that the substrate compacts by gravity, cutting off gas exchange to the bottom of the jar.<br /><br />If you feel that bigger cakes give bigger fruits, simply stack two half pint cakes on top of each other after birthing.&nbsp; However, I've not seen pint cakes produce larger fruits on a regular basis, and the grower who recently used 1/4 pint cakes had great results.&nbsp; Another grower a few years ago used shot glasses with wonderful results.&nbsp; With the brf tek, smaller substrates are the way to go.<br />RR","title":"Re: 1/2 pint jars vs. full pint jars"}}